    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 1: Land Title & Ownership – Who Actually Owns the Land?
      </h2>
      <p>
        Most buyers directly jump to price, amenities, and view. But the real
        foundation of a project is not cement – it’s the <strong>title</strong>
        of the land. If the title is unclear, disputed, or jointly owned
        without proper approvals, you are literally building your dream home on
        legal quicksand.
      </p>
      <p>At minimum, you want clarity on three things:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Who currently owns the land?</li>
        <li>Is the land free from loans, claims, or disputes?</li>
        <li>Is the land legally allowed to be used for this type of project?</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Ask for and independently verify these documents:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Title Deed:</strong> Confirms who owns the land right now.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Encumbrance Certificate (EC):</strong> Shows if the property
          is free from financial or legal liability, usually checked over the
          last 15–30 years.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Mother Deed:</strong> Shows the chain of ownership over time.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Land Use & Zoning Approvals:</strong> Confirms whether
          residential construction is allowed on that parcel.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Never rely only on the builder’s in-house legal team for this. Spend
        money on an <strong>independent property lawyer</strong> whose only
        loyalty is towards you.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Mini Checklist – Land Title</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Get copies of title deed, EC, mother deed.</li>
          <li>Ask your own lawyer to verify and give a written opinion.</li>
          <li>Confirm land use permissions for residential construction.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 2: RERA Registration – Non-Negotiable, No Excuses
      </h2>
      <p>
        If there is one single filter that instantly eliminates a large chunk
        of risky projects, it’s this: <strong>Is the project registered on the
        state’s RERA website?</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        You will often hear phrases like “RERA is under process”, “approvals
        coming in 2–3 weeks”, or “this is a soft launch before RERA”. That’s a
        polite way of saying: <strong>you are taking the risk, not us</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        A RERA-registered project gives you visibility into the official
        promised possession date, approved layout plans, land details, and any
        complaints or litigation. It doesn’t guarantee perfection, but it
        removes many of the darkest red flags.
      </p>
      <p>
        Always go to your state’s RERA portal, search by project name or
        builder name, and cross-check:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>RERA registration number</li>
        <li>Project start and estimated completion date</li>
        <li>Approved floor plans and layout</li>
        <li>Land title details and any reported issues</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-red-200 bg-red-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Red Flag: Common Marketing Trap</p>
        <p>
          Ads and hoardings loudly scream “RERA APPROVED”, but the project name
          on RERA is slightly different or refers to only one phase. Always
          cross-verify exact names and phase numbers, not just logos and
          branding.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Mini Checklist – RERA</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Independently search the project on the official RERA website.</li>
          <li>Match project name, builder, and phase details carefully.</li>
          <li>
            Compare brochure promises with what’s officially committed under
            RERA.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 3: Builder Track Record – Are They Finishers or Just Sellers?
      </h2>
      <p>
        A builder’s <strong>history of delivering projects</strong> is one of
        the best indicators of your project’s future. Marketing can be easily
        copied. Execution cannot.
      </p>
      <p>Look at the last 5–10 years and ask:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>How many projects have they launched vs completed?</li>
        <li>
          What was the actual delay vs promised possession (if any) in previous
          projects?
        </li>
        <li>What do existing residents say about quality and service?</li>
        <li>
          Are there any major legal disputes, fraud cases, or RERA penalties
          against them?
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Visit at least one completed project by the same developer. Don’t just
        see the gate and clubhouse – walk into the staircases, basement,
        parking, lift lobbies, and common areas. Poor maintenance, water
        leakage, bad finishing and unresolved issues tell you how the builder
        behaves after selling.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Mini Checklist – Builder Reputation</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Visit at least one older delivered project.</li>
          <li>Talk to 2–3 existing residents without a salesperson around.</li>
          <li>Search online for complaints, forum discussions, and RERA orders.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 4: Brochure vs Reality – Sample Flats, Renders & On-Ground Truth
      </h2>
      <p>
        A sample flat is not a promise. It’s a <strong>sales tool</strong>.
        Developers often use better tiles, fittings, furniture, and false
        ceilings than what will be delivered as “standard”.
      </p>
      <p>
        Marketing teams also love using CGI renders – blue skies, lush green
        lawns, wide roads, cafes, office towers, and metro lines magically
        surrounding the property.
      </p>
      <p>
        Your job is to pierce through this layer. Visit the actual site:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Check whether any real structural work has started.</li>
        <li>Compare the approved floor plan with the sample flat layout.</li>
        <li>Document specifications: brands of fittings, tiles, doors, windows.</li>
        <li>Ask what counts as “standard” and what is extra cost.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-yellow-200 bg-yellow-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Reality Check Exercise</p>
        <p>
          Take photos and short videos during your site visit. When you go back
          home, compare them with the brochure and 3D visuals. Anywhere you see
          a big mismatch, ask direct questions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 5: Full Cost Breakdown – Not Just “Starting From” Price
      </h2>
      <p>
        The phrase “<strong>Starting at ₹49 lakhs</strong>” is designed to
        anchor you emotionally. In reality, that price might be for the lowest
        floor, worst view, smallest configuration, with half the things marked
        as “optional”.
      </p>
      <p>Ask for a full written cost sheet including:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Base price per sq. ft (clearly mention carpet vs super built-up)</li>
        <li>Floor rise charges</li>
        <li>Clubhouse & amenity charges</li>
        <li>Parking (open/covered/stilt) charges</li>
        <li>Maintenance deposit and corpus fund</li>
        <li>Legal, documentation, and registration charges</li>
        <li>GST or any other applicable taxes</li>
        <li>“Preferred location” or “view” charges, if applicable</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Build your own Excel sheet or even a simple handwritten table, and
        calculate the <strong>all-inclusive on-road price</strong>. That’s the
        real number you are committing to.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Mini Checklist – Cost & Affordability</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Get a detailed cost sheet on email or letterhead.</li>
          <li>
            Compare 2–3 projects on final “all-in” price, not headline offers.
          </li>
          <li>
            Stress test: Can you still comfortably pay EMIs if interest rates
            rise by 1–2%?
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 6: Location & Future Development – Hype vs Ground Reality
      </h2>
      <p>
        One of the strongest marketing tricks in real estate is “future
        potential”. Terms like “upcoming IT corridor”, “next financial hub”,
        and “future metro connectivity” are powerful – and often loosely used.
      </p>
      <p>To separate hype from reality:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Use Google Maps to check actual distance to your workplace, school,
          hospital, and key city areas.
        </li>
        <li>
          Look at government master plans, official metro/road project
          documents, not just maps drawn in the brochure.
        </li>
        <li>
          Visit the area at different times of day to see traffic, safety, and
          basic infrastructure.
        </li>
        <li>
          Talk to local shopkeepers and residents – they often know more about
          real timelines than any brochure.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A remote plot of land being sold as “future city centre” may or may not
        become reality. Your EMIs, however, will start immediately.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 7: Approvals & Legal Documentation – The Boring Part That Saves You
      </h2>
      <p>
        Approvals don’t look sexy on Instagram, but they are what protects your
        money in the real world. Before you go anywhere near an agreement, you
        want clarity on:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Building plan approval from relevant authorities</li>
        <li>
          Commencement Certificate (CC) confirming they are permitted to start
          construction
        </li>
        <li>
          NOCs from fire department, water, electricity, and environment
          (where applicable)
        </li>
        <li>
          Draft copy of the Sale Agreement and Construction Agreement you’ll be
          signing
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Get the draft agreement in advance, send it to your lawyer, and ask
        them to highlight:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Penalty clauses for delayed possession</li>
        <li>What happens if approvals are further delayed</li>
        <li>Any one-sided clauses heavily favouring the builder</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Mini Checklist – Approvals</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Ask for all approval copies, not just verbal assurance.</li>
          <li>Get your lawyer’s written review of the agreement.</li>
          <li>Check if possession timelines and penalties are clearly defined.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 8: Realistic Valuation, Resale & Rental Potential
      </h2>
      <p>
        Many buyers only look at “Can I afford the EMI?” and ignore “Will this
        property hold or grow its value if I need to sell or rent it later?”.
      </p>
      <p>
        Compare with other projects in the same micro-market on <strong>carpet
        area price</strong>, not just super built-up. Analyze:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Availability of similar units in resale listings</li>
        <li>
          Current rental rates in that area for similar size and quality
          apartments
        </li>
        <li>
          How dependent the location is on one single factor (e.g. one tech
          park)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A slightly higher price in a mature, well-connected, livable area may
        be a better long-term decision than a cheap “bet” in the middle of
        nowhere.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 9: Bank Loan Tie-ups – Silent Due Diligence You Can Leverage
      </h2>
      <p>
        Banks are not emotional; they are brutally practical. Before they agree
        to fund a project, their legal and technical teams do their own checks
        on land title, approvals, and builder reputation.
      </p>
      <p>
        If multiple major banks and housing finance companies have approved the
        project, it is usually a positive sign. If only one unknown NBFC is
        offering funding, or the builder keeps pushing you towards a specific
        small financer, ask why.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Mini Checklist – Bank Funding</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>
            Ask which banks have officially approved the project (get proof).
          </li>
          <li>Cross-check with the bank directly, not only via builder staff.</li>
          <li>
            If big banks are avoiding the project, treat that as a serious
            warning signal.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Check 10: Real Reviews, Residents & Reputation – Beyond Ads & Influencers
      </h2>
      <p>
        Builders today hire influencers, run polished video campaigns, and
        sponsor content that looks like “unbiased reviews”. You have to cut
        through that and find people who have actually lived with this builder’s
        quality.
      </p>
      <p>Some places to look:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>YouTube walkthroughs by residents or independent reviewers</li>
        <li>Google Maps reviews of existing projects by the same developer</li>
        <li>City-specific real estate forums and Telegram/WhatsApp groups</li>
        <li>Conversations with security staff, maintenance teams, and locals</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A 10-minute conversation with an existing resident of a five-year-old
        project is often more valuable than a one-hour presentation from the
        sales team.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-5 rounded-2xl border border-emerald-200 bg-emerald-50 p-4 text-sm">
        <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Mini Checklist – Reputation</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>
            Talk to at least 2 residents of a completed project by the same
            builder.
          </li>
          <li>
            Ask: “If you had to buy again today, would you choose the same
            builder?”
          </li>
          <li>Note recurring complaints about quality, delays, or support.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">
        Common Real Estate Marketing Traps You Should Learn to Spot
      </h2>
      <p>
        Alongside the 10 checks, it helps to recognize the psychological
        triggers developers use to rush your decision:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>“Pre-launch offer – lowest price ever”</strong><br />
          You are being paid with a discount to take on the highest risk phase.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>“Last few units left”</strong><br />
          Often used even when half the inventory is unsold. Designed to create
          fear of missing out.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>“Assured rentals / guaranteed buyback”</strong><br />
          If rental returns were genuinely guaranteed, institutions – not
          retail buyers – would be lining up.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>“Metro/highway coming soon”</strong><br />
          The timeline for infrastructure is usually 8–15 years, not 18 months.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>“Zero cost EMI / subvention scheme”</strong><br />
          The cost is usually baked into the price somewhere else.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

