        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            1. What is the first thing I should check before booking any flat?
          </h3>
          <p>
            The very first filter is legality: land title and RERA registration.
            Before you discuss price, view, or scheme, confirm that the project
            is registered on the state RERA portal and that the land has clear,
            dispute-free title. This alone eliminates many risky options.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            2. Is it safe to invest in a pre-launch real estate project?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Pre-launch projects carry the highest risk because approvals may not
            be fully in place, and construction may not have started. While the
            price can look attractive, you are effectively funding the earliest,
            riskiest phase. Unless you fully understand and can absorb that
            risk, it’s better to choose RERA-registered projects with visible
            progress and clear timelines.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            3. How do I know if a real estate price is fair in a particular area?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Don’t rely only on the builder’s quote. Compare carpet-area prices
            across 3–4 similar projects nearby, check recent resale listings,
            and speak to at least one local broker. If a project is priced
            significantly above everything else without a clear reason (like
            location advantage, brand, or specs), you may be paying a heavy
            “hype premium”.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            4. Do I really need a property lawyer if the bank has approved my loan?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Bank due diligence is helpful, but it’s done from the lender’s
            risk-management perspective, not your personal long-term interest.
            A property lawyer working only for you will review title, approvals,
            and agreement terms in far more detail and highlight clauses that
            might hurt you later (like one-sided penalty rules or vague
            handover commitments).
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            5. What are the biggest hidden costs when buying a flat?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Common hidden (or under-communicated) costs include floor rise
            charges, club membership and amenities, parking, maintenance deposit
            and corpus fund, legal and documentation fees, and taxes. Always ask
            for a full cost sheet and calculate the all-inclusive on-road price
            before deciding affordability.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            6. How can I verify that a brochure’s future infrastructure claims are real?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Cross-check every claim (metro line, ring road, flyover, IT park)
            with official government announcements, project documents, or
            credible news sources. If the salesperson cannot show any official
            proof and keeps saying “it’s coming, everyone knows”, treat it as
            marketing, not fact. Plan your decision on what exists today, not
            just what might happen 10 years later.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            7. What is the difference between carpet area and super built-up area?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Carpet area is the usable area inside your flat – the space you
            can actually walk on. Super built-up area includes your flat’s
            carpet area plus a proportion of common areas like lobbies,
            staircases, and amenities. Pricing is often quoted on super
            built-up, but your livable space is carpet. Always compare projects
            on carpet-area pricing for a fair view.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            8. Are celebrity endorsements or influencer reviews a sign of a good project?
          </h3>
          <p>
            No. Celebrity endorsements and influencer videos are marketing
            tools. They say nothing about long-term quality, legal safety, or
            builder ethics. Treat them as entertainment, not evidence. Actual
            proof comes from documents, approvals, track record, and real
            residents’ experiences.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            9. Can I negotiate the price with the builder?
          </h3>
          <p>
            In many markets, there is room to negotiate, especially on
            floor-rise charges, parking, or extra fees. However, don’t make
            your decision purely on who offers the biggest discount. A slightly
            higher price with better legality, location, and construction
            quality is often the smarter, safer choice over the long run.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            10. How do I protect myself from delayed possession?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Choose RERA-registered projects, review the possession date and
            penalty clauses in your agreement, and check the builder’s history
            on past delivery. If the agreement has vague wording or no penalty
            for delays, ask for clarification or reconsider the project
            altogether.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            11. Is it better to buy under-construction or ready-to-move property?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Ready-to-move homes remove possession delay risk and let you see
            exactly what you are buying, but prices may be higher. Under-
            construction can be cheaper initially but carries completion and
            approval risk. If you choose under-construction, be extra strict
            with the 10 checks in this article.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">
            12. I feel overwhelmed by all these checks. Where should I start?
          </h3>
          <p>
            Start simple: 1) Verify RERA, 2) Verify land title via a lawyer, 3)
            Visit one older project by the same builder. These three steps
            alone will give you a much clearer picture. From there, layer on
            the cost sheet, approvals, bank tie-ups, and resident feedback. You
            don’t have to do everything in one day – but you must do it before
            you commit your life savings.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
